english:
  title: A Memorial Against Buddhism
  language: eng
  text: |-
    We humble servants, though of limited capacity, have been fortunate to study the Sacred Learning within the Confucian temple in this prosperous age. Thus we have some acquaintance with heterodox doctrines.

    The harm wrought by Buddhism is manifold indeed. It teaches the absence of father and sovereign, corrupts the human heart, and destroys the social order. Only by refuting it can we restore true governance. Its followers idle and consume without labor, evade taxation, and siphon the people's wealth. Only by expelling them can we benefit the common folk. Thus Mencius said, "I wish to rectify the human heart and eliminate false teachings." Those who expound this say, "The harm of Buddhism exceeds even that of Yang Zhu and Mo Di." They further say, "When false teachings harm the true way, all people may oppose them—not only the sage. Just as in the Spring and Autumn Annals, any person may punish rebellious ministers and traitors, not only the magistrate." And again, "For scholars, a hairsbreadth's deviation in understanding right and wrong brings harm upon the people and calamity to future generations." The ancients guarded against Buddhism with such rigor because when our teaching prevails, the social bonds are ordered and all under heaven finds peace. When heterodoxy flourishes, these bonds dissolve and chaos reigns. If that doctrine were to spread unchecked and all the world were to follow it, what ruler could even govern, though Yao and Shun themselves returned?

    Yet your Highness has already comprehended this matter well and made the proper judgments. We shall not belabor the argument further, but speak only to the events of our present day. We humbly beseech Your Highness's consideration.

    We hold that the ruler is the model for all people, and the capital is the root from which all provinces grow. What the ruler favors, the people revere. What the capital values, the provinces emulate. The influence spreads as swiftly as shadow follows form. How then can such matters not be approached with utmost care?

    In recent years, drought and deluge have alternated. Since the year of Bing-chen, famine has grown ever more severe. The elderly among the people languish in ditches; the vigorous scatter to the four directions—thousands upon thousands have fled. Surely this is the time for poor relief, frugality, and care for the common folk.

    Yet in the year of Ding-si, when Heungcheon Temple was magnificently restored and grand construction began, the state treasuries poured forth vast sums for offerings and donations. Though it may employ the idle, from whence comes the cost of such provisions? Surely it extracts the lifeblood of our people to create useless empty vessels. We harbored misgivings then. When the censorate remonstrated, Your Highness replied that the temple was founded by the ancestors and you could not bear to see it fall to ruin. We accepted this reasoning. Yet how could we have foreseen it would reach such extremes?

    Moreover, the farming season has just begun, and for months now there has been no rain. The portents resemble those of the year Bing-chen. Our people face true hardship and deserve compassion. Yet the monks of Heungcheon, precisely at this moment, exploit the people's resources through a hundred schemes. They compose persuasive writings, bearing the seals of royal relatives, which circulate through city and countryside, spreading false promises and deluding the ignorant masses. Through tales of karmic consequence and otherworldly punishment, they frighten people into bankrupting their households without thought of the hunger that surely awaits them. Thus they steal the people's wealth and amass enormous granaries. In the great city's center, they hold grand gatherings for residence monks, brazenly operating without restraint or legal impediment. High and low alike abandon themselves to this current—the entire nation vies to feed the Buddha and sponsor monastic feasts.

    While the wealthy might afford such expenditure, even the destitute exhaust themselves in these practices, only to perish in the gutters—like moths drawn to the flame, heedless of their doom. Alas! The capital should be the source of civilization's ways, yet it has become merely a place of incense and worship. When the provinces see this and follow suit, their departures from propriety shall exceed even what we now observe. Any person possessed of wisdom must lament this gravely.

    Recently, the censorate, grasping this very concern, has submitted memorials protesting vigorously. We deemed this a great blessing for the realm. Yet imagine our dismay when Your Highness declined to heed them! Not only did you refuse to listen—you commanded the imperial guard to post soldiers at the temple's gates, arrayed on all sides, preventing all entry and exit. The fortress is sealed as tightly as the inner palaces themselves, impenetrable even to the censorate's authority. Who then can restrain them from committing further outrages? Upon reflection, even we in our foolishness find this unbearable. How much more so must it trouble Your Highness's sacred mind?

    We have also heard that in the waning days of the former dynasty, a monk named Lazy Patriarch spread teachings of extinction and delusion among the foolish masses, earning the title "living Buddha." He brought princes to their knees in obeisance to a beggar. The kingdom's fortune declined, and Confucian learning withered. Fortunately, men of true principle uprooted his legacy, bringing about his ultimate destruction—a great blessing for that faltering state. Yet consider our Great Ancestor, the Kangheun Daeking, who despite his overwhelming duties in founding the realm, remained vigilant against Buddhism's corruption and strictly regulated monastic orders. The Taejong, the Gongjeong Daeking, clearly perceived their defects and reduced temples to one or two in ten, appropriating their lands for military provisions, refusing to build temples at royal burial sites. Such was his vigilance in repelling the heterodox and restoring the way!

    Our present Sovereign, inheriting the legacy of these two sages with the virtue of Yao and Shun, judged that reform must begin within the palace. He eliminated the Hall of Internal Vows, reduced the monastic order, forbade monks entry to cities, and prohibited young men from becoming monks. Thus the clergy restrained themselves, dared not act with abandon, and we servants rejoiced to see the Confucian way ascending day by day. How could we have imagined heterodoxy would resurface? How could we have imagined it would flourish as it now does?

    Yet Heungcheon remains unmoved by history's lesson, and its abbot fancies himself successor to that Lazy Patriarch, seeking through his teachings to transform the customs of the realm. The people's reverence for him matches what they once held for that ancient deceiver. Even the royal kinfolk, unmindful of their station's dignity, prostrate themselves as his disciples. Each time we witness such scenes, we grip our robes in anguish.

    Now we hear—though we dare not confirm it—that Your Highness has gifted treasures of jade and silken brocade to fashion monastic vestments, adorned the meditation halls with gold and silver, and bestowed golden utensils, spoons, chopsticks, and prayer beads upon the abbot himself. Is this truly so? We cannot sleep for sorrow and weep at the thought.

    The common people's wavering faith in Buddhism remains because the sagacious ruler above upholds the Confucian way and honors it as the true path. Yet if Your Highness grants such gifts, though your own intent may be innocent, will not the monks boast of this, and the people at large not say, "If even the Sage Lord does this, how much more should we?" Thus from the royal household down through all the masses, people will rush to make offerings and prostrations, seeking discipleship, hoping for karmic blessing. The movement swells without limit. This is like training the saplings toward the heavens—like removing the dams that check the waters' flow. How can those concerned for the Confucian way not grow cold with dread?

    Moreover, gold and silver are not produced in our realm. We have earnestly petitioned the Middle Kingdom to remit these as tribute. Should they hear of this matter, what would they say of Your Highness? And since the sovereign's every deed is inscribed in history, if gold and silver remittances are recorded as ceased, only to be followed by records of golden prayer beads bestowed, what will historians of a thousand years hence say of you as a ruler?

    One might counter: "The abbot has already attained the Buddha's way." Yet since the Han and Tang, countless have patronized Buddhism, and none have been known to enjoy its blessings for their state. The King of Chu, though devoted, ended in great punishment. The Warrior Emperor of Liang, though reverent, could not escape starvation in his final capital. Thus Buddhism's futility for nation and people is clear. Moreover, if purity and desirelessness are Buddhism's teaching, then practitioners should dwell in mountain hermitages, sit in silent meditation, wear rough robes, fast entirely, and illuminate their path through austerity. Yet we hear of colored silks, fine foods, and ostentatious display in the streets. Is this not a mockery? They propagate teachings that abolish kinship and eliminate propriety, seducing the world and deceiving the masses. We fear that in years to come, the entire realm will fall under the sway of the fatherless, kingless teaching, all becoming shaven-headed disciples, and humanity itself shall perish. Even now we see that those newly ordained in a single year number nearly ten thousand—a harbinger of mankind's end! This surely springs from their recruitment.

    In the former dynasty's decline, when they still possessed the wisdom to execute Lazy Patriarch and purge such filth, how much more should our sage age defend against it? We humbly beseech you to cast off doubt, root out evil with firmness, and command your officials to remove but one abbot's head, thereby severing the heterodoxy's source. Thus would the realm find great fortune.

    We have also heard that fragrance and foul odor cannot share a vessel, nor can truth and falsehood coexist. Thus the superior person abhors when purple confounds vermillion, and the wise guard against presumption born of confusion. The boundary between our Confucian way and Buddhism is far starker than the difference between incense and stench. Yet in the triennial examinations, you select monks of both orders as if they were civil and military officials. Though the state may weigh these differently in its treatment, the examination method itself resembles ours. Thus the Buddhists claim that Confucianism and Buddhism share the same spirit. Is this not purple confounding vermillion? Is this not presumption born of confusion? Moreover, examinations were instituted to discover talent, and talent should be put to use. Yet what use could monks possibly serve that would justify this examination? This is but a useless system of error, fit only for the ridicule of future generations. We take further exception to this.

    We have surveyed the temples and found posted at their gates a proclamation stating: "By order of the Ritual Minister's Attendant, Nyom Jo, from this day forth, Confucian scholars are forbidden from visiting temples for recreation." We cannot discern whether Your Highness intended this to prevent students' idleness and study's abandonment through your reverence for learning, or whether you meant to prevent the defilement of the Buddha's relics through your faith in Buddhism. Can it be that the Ministry of Ritual, the source of proper ceremonies, and its highest officials, the sovereign's voice, now author words condemning Confucians and display them above the gates of monks? Our Confucian way is thus rejected by the heterodoxy while the throne remains unmoved. This wounds the heart beyond measure.

    We have heard that when rulers enjoy prolonged peace, they cease to fear their people and minister to their needs. If no foreign threat arises to sharpen their attention, they inevitably drift toward Buddhism and Daoism, gradually declining until their kingdom belongs to them no longer. The examples of the Han's Mingdi and Liang's Wudi serve as mirrors. Though in this sage age we fear no such calamity, if the roots are not entirely severed, how can we guarantee that in ten thousand generations there shall arise no new Mingdi or Wudi? This is a grave cause for concern. Yet the great ministers of the court remain silent, offering no counsel, and the censorate's remonstrations lack true fervor. How can this accord with the duty to promote the good and suppress evil, or with the principle of maintaining the state's eternal strength?

    The ancients said, "Founding a dynasty is easy; preserving it is hard." A hundred years of building scarcely equals a single day of destruction. Thus Baik Ik admonished the great Shun against idle wandering, and the Duke of Zhou warned King Cheng against licentiousness. When dwelling in prosperity and possessing a perfected realm, the descent into peril arises from a single moment's inattention.

    Since Your Highness's enthronement, you have been careful, devoted all energy to governance, readily heeded remonstrations, and welcomed counsel from all. No false teachings clouded your judgment. Yet now, as you approach our present day, the reverence and care that once animated you have gradually waned. The heterodoxy's poison spreads unchecked. We fear that the peace we have built begins to crumble even now, and the people's hopes founder. The Changes say: "Heaven moves with vigor; thus the superior person unceasingly exerts himself." The Documents say: "When beginning and end are one, this is renewal." We humbly beseech you: do not think that a single moment's negligence harms nothing, nor that one error wounds the governance. Draw upon perfect sincerity to emulate heaven's vigorous motion. Strengthen yourself unceasingly as the superior person does. Deepen your resolve of old and preserve forever your ancestors' legacy. Thus would the state and ancestral temple find great fortune, and the Confucian way find great fortune.
  footnotes:
    - 'Lazy Patriarch (懶翁): A historical Buddhist figure from the late Goryeo period who gained immense political influence. This memorial compares the contemporary abbot favorably to him as a warning of the dangers of unchecked monastic power.'
    - The year Bing-chen refers to 1436 (the year before this memorial was likely written in 1437), when severe famine struck Korea.
    - The reference to 'one abbot's head' suggests the memorial's author advocated for executing the temple's abbot as a decisive measure against Buddhism's influence.
    - The mention of gold and silver as non-products of Korea reflects the tributary system where Korea sent these materials to China; their use for Buddhist purposes was seen as a shameful misuse of state resources.
    - The 'Middle Kingdom' (上國) refers to China, to which Korea maintained a tributary relationship during the Joseon period.
